title: [S2 Ep #2] The Tornado Cash Fallout, Privacy Tech and Bitcoin's Fee Market
description:
‍In this episode of the Surus Podcast, Form & Structure, Neha Narula from MIT's Digital Currency Initiative and Ethan Heilman from Cloudflare join Patrick Murck to discuss the Roman Storm verdict and its impact on privacy tool development, Bitcoin's fee market breakdown and the "one sat per vbyte" policy problem, and Ethan's evolving perspective on long-term network resilience – shifting from "Bitcoin is doomed if X happens" to asking "how do we ensure Bitcoin survives 100+ years."

Highlights from the conversation:
- The Chilling Effect on Developers: Neha reveals how the Tornado Cash and Roman Storm cases are creating widespread fear among privacy developers: "I've definitely had conversations with folks about Samurai and Tornado Cash, and a lot of developers who work even adjacent to privacy preserving stuff are scared."Policy vs. Consensus Breakdown: The discussion explores Bitcoin's current infrastructure crisis where monitoring nodes must request approximately 0.8 megabytes of transactions per block—transactions they never saw on the peer-to-peer network due to the "one sat per vbyte" minimum policy.The Money Transmitter Problem: Patrick breaks down how the broad interpretation of US Code 1960 in the Roman Storm case raises questions about whether "releasing a decentralized service counts as a violation" and creates uncertainty that could affect anyone from Google distributing Chrome to developers publishing open source code.Centralization Pressures: Ethan explains how the fee market breakdown forces smaller miners to validate blocks more slowly than larger miners who have direct transaction access, creating competitive disadvantages that threaten Bitcoin's decentralized structure.
From Crisis to Century-Long Thinking: The conversation addresses Ethan's philosophical shift from catastrophic thinking to constructive long-term planning: moving from "Bitcoin is doomed if X happens" to asking "how do we ensure Bitcoin survives the next 100+ years" by securing the UTXO set against future cryptographic breaks.The Developer Resource Drain: Neha highlights how even legitimate developers now spend "days and weeks" trying to understand their legal exposure instead of building, while lacking resources to properly consult attorneys about compliance questions.
